you drives at night in the middle of a thunderstorm.
his high beams illuminate a large tree. you can see something huddled under the tree...people? you decide to investigate. you park the car and grab your umbrella. as you leave the car and approach the tree, there are four grillers huddled together under the tree.
"you kids shouldn't be out here at this time."
you peer closer. two of the girls are crying. the other two are trying to stay warm.
"do you need a lift home?"
the girl with the long yellow hair sniffles. "we don't have a home anymore."
oh. ohhhh.
"well, do you know how to contact your folks?"
"we don't have parents, sir..."
the one with the glasses scoffs. "like they'd ever want us back after that stunt."
so, no parents, no home, abandoned for something you could only imagine was bad enough to kick four young girls out into the pouring rain. what the hell kind of place did these girls come from?
you don't have many options. the girls are soaked and cold. the least you could do is give them a warm bed before contacting the police.
"look, you can't be out here, right? how about i let you stay the night at my place?"
the girls don't appear to trust you, but a nearby clap of thunder makes them reconsider immediately. they rush to your car. three pile into the back, the girl with the yellow pigtails sits in the front seat.
you drive home, occasionally looking at the girls in the mirror. the girl with the long yellow hair is holding the girl with the purple dress, who seems the most miserable. the girl with the glasses stares out the window.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
your house wasn't meant to host guests, but there are enough sofas and blankets to keep four girls warm.
the girls silently leave their shoes at the door and walk inside shivering. you usher them to the bathroom and grab some casual shirts and shorts to let them wear.
"it's the best i can do on short notice. leave the wet clothes in the tub. i'll do the laundry."
the girls take turns in the shower and come out feeling warmer. you don't have much food to offer so you prepare some butter sandwiches and leave some peanut butter and other spreads out for them.
after dinner, you sit down and talk to them. the girls tell you their names: junko (glasses), sandra (purple dress), chiho (golden hair) and anna (pigtails), and that they lived in a large complex with lots of people. they won't tell you what they did, but you don't pressure them.
you spend the rest of the night watching television with them. the girls are all different. sandra and chiho seem most affected by being abandoned and spend the whole time being close. sandra looks very miserable and cries the most, and chiho holds her and whispers things to her that you can't hear. junko is closed off and doesn't like to talk with the others. anna occasionally talks to the others and seems the least affected.
at midnight, you decide to let the girls sleep. before you go, sandra asks to be hugged. you hug her.

all the girls pile on top of you and hug you. even junko seems really happy.
“i’m going to organize everything so that i can legally adopt you.”

posts.com:
you spoke with police and the people who lived in the complex (one was a nazi, which only strengthened your desire to get the girls away from these people). you could see the complex was heavily damaged, perhaps it was what got the girls kicked out.
after some background checks were passed and paperwork signed, you became the legal guardian of anna, chiho, junko and sandra. it was a harrowing but relieving moment for you, and your new daughters cried once the last document was notarized
the first thing you did was reshuffle your home. you cleaned out a large spare room and bought two bunks for the girls to sleep in. you also bought a toy chest, a desk, a computer and lots of toys, installed a closet, and bought them clothes (all the girls had their own specific styles but you had the money to get exactly what they wanted).
all your daughters were between 9 and 11 years old and, from what you learned, never attended school. you considered enrolling them, but they all objected. they all actually seemed smart on their own, so you offered to homeschool them and, when the time came, you’d be able to enrol them in college
the first few months of fatherhood were very turbulent. the girls all had emotional distress to sort out. chiho felt the loss of her old life. sandra lost her old friends and felt guilty because apparently she had the idea for the incident. junko repressed a lot but in private she cried into your shoulder about being too scared to open up. anna was mostly chill, but she opened up about feeling like she didn’t have a purpose. you listened patiently and offered support to the girls, whether it be hugs or stroking their hair.
